  15:QX_Protocol.c **** 
  16:QX_Protocol.c **** 	Filename: "QX_Protocol.c"
  17:QX_Protocol.c **** 
  18:QX_Protocol.c **** 	Description: This file provides the non-project specific portions of the Freefly QX Protocol
  19:QX_Protocol.c **** 
  20:QX_Protocol.c **** 	Reuse and Porting:
  21:QX_Protocol.c **** 	This code is design for simple reuse in other projects
  22:QX_Protocol.c **** 	by separation of the protocol code/data from the application code/data.
  23:QX_Protocol.c **** 	Steps:
  24:QX_Protocol.c **** 	1.	Include QX_Protocol.c/.h and QX_Parsing_Util.c/.h files in your new project. 
  25:QX_Protocol.c **** 		These should not be modified for the application.
  26:QX_Protocol.c **** 	2.	Write the QX_Protocol_App.c/.h files. Other projects can be used as a template.
  27:QX_Protocol.c **** 		This contains the client/server parser callback functions, support functions, 
  28:QX_Protocol.c **** 		and QX_SendMsg2CommsPort_CB() which should send the messages to the desired port.
  29:QX_Protocol.c **** 		The message support arrays (QX_Cli_MsgSupport and QX_Srv_MsgSupport)
  30:QX_Protocol.c **** 		should also be initialized with the supported messages and their length check enforcement status.
  31:QX_Protocol.c **** 	3. Define the number of servers and clients in your system by defining QX_NUM_SRV and QX_NUM_CLI i
  32:QX_Protocol.c **** 	4. Assign parser callback functions for each client and server using QX_InitSrv() and QX_InitCli()
  33:QX_Protocol.c **** 	5. Call the QX_Init() function at application startup.
  34:QX_Protocol.c **** 	6. In a periodic loop (main, or control/comms task) call QX_StreamRxCharSM() for each port to rece
  35:QX_Protocol.c **** 	7. Send any unsolicited messages such periodic current value messages (charting) and client read/w
  36:QX_Protocol.c **** 
  37:QX_Protocol.c **** 	There are 3 Main Message Types that can be sent via QX:
  38:QX_Protocol.c **** 	CURRENT VALUE - Sent by server in response to read, write or periodically (charting). Recieved by 
  39:QX_Protocol.c **** 	READ - Sent by client to request that a current value message be sent by server as a reply.
  40:QX_Protocol.c **** 	WRITE (Absolute or Relative) - Sent by client to write data. Triggers a current value response by 
  41:QX_Protocol.c **** 		
  42:QX_Protocol.c **** -----------------------------------------------------------------*/
  43:QX_Protocol.c **** 
  44:QX_Protocol.c **** //****************************************************************************
  45:QX_Protocol.c **** // Headers
  46:QX_Protocol.c **** //****************************************************************************
  47:QX_Protocol.c **** #include "QX_Protocol.h"			// Protocol Header
  48:QX_Protocol.c **** #include "QX_App_Config.h"			// Configure application specific values in this file
  49:QX_Protocol.c **** #include "QX_Protocol_App.h"		// This contains the application specific interface functions
  50:QX_Protocol.c **** #include "QX_Parsing_Functions.h"	// Contains utility functions for parsing data in/out of raw buff
  51:QX_Protocol.c **** #include <stdlib.h>
  52:QX_Protocol.c **** #include <stdint.h>		// for Standard Data Types
  53:QX_Protocol.c **** #include <string.h>		// for array and string manipulation
  54:QX_Protocol.c **** 
